5) Problem statement

Explain the problem statement. The problem statement must include:

  1. The problem

  2. Is it a regression or classification problem or a combination of both?

  3. Is it an inference or prediction problem or a combination of both?

  4. How will you assess model accuracy?

  • If it is a classification problem, then which measure(s) will you optimize for your model â precision, recall, false negative rate (FNR), accuracy, ROC-AUC etc., and why?
  • If it is a regression problem, then which measure(s) will you optimize for your model â RMSE (Root mean squared error), MAE (mean absolute error), maximum absolute error etc., and why?
  1. What techniques do you think you may need to use to improve your model? If you have too many variables, some of which are correlated or collinear, you may need to do variable selection (techniques for variable selection that you will learn later in the course - stepwise regression, lasso, ridge regression). If the variables do not have a linear relationship with the response, or if some of the modeling assumptions are not satisfied, you may need to transform the predictors and/or the response (variable transformation) to obtain a better fit.

(5 points)

  1. The problem statement is to create a model based on various clinical and demographic features (such as BMI, gender, glucose level, and other factors) of a patient to determine if they are likely to have stroke.

  2. This will be a classification problem because the analysis of stroke likelihood is a categorical variable.

  3. This will also require both prediction and inference: we will use the model to predict stroke likelihood based on the features and also use the model to infer which of the predictors have the strongest association with a higher likelihood of a stroke incidence.

  4. To assess model accuracy, we want to minimize the FNR specifically since our stakeholders include people who are at risk of having strokes, and we would rather overpredict people who would get a stroke to be cautious than to accidentally not tell someone that they are at risk of stroke if they do end up getting one (which would be a false positive). However, since most of the people in the dataset did not end up having strokes (the low stroke incidence is featured in the bottom right corner of the pairplot showing stroke distribution), we would want to have our model mirror this by mostly assigning 0âs to people (no stroke), so our model will ideally have high precision and low recall even though we want to specifically minimize FNR.

  5. First, look at the correlations of the variables in the data.

Code 
stroke_data['stroke'].value_counts() / stroke_data['stroke'].count()
0    0.951272
1    0.048728
Name: stroke, dtype: float64

Since we know what the outcomes are already (if a patient had a stroke or not), we want our model to do better than guessing 50/50 if the patient did or did not have a stroke, and because the incidence of stroke in this dataset is around 5%, we would also want our model to do a better job than just assuming every random person had a 5% chance of getting stroke to assess the accuracy of our testing. However, we should still expect that our model will classify most people as not getting a stroke since there is such a low incidence of stroke in the data. We want to be accurate enough to get results close to this 5% incidence, and anything that is around the average stroke incidence in the US should be acceptable so that we can reassure our stakeholders that our results are valid.
